LAWS3220 Learning Outcomes

Upon completing of the course students should be able to:

1. Understand the law and practice relating to backing and the means by which this affects and regulates the day to day practice of banks in Hong Kong
2. Understand the law and practice relating to banking transactions, both between banks and between banks and their customers.
3. Apply this legal knowledge to practical situations.

## Subject-specific abilities

At the conclusion of this module, students will be able to:

1critically evaluate the contribution of legal institutions in the creation of strong and vibrant banking markets

2identify the main components of the essential legal framework underpinning modern banking systems

3identify and discuss the main components of the financial system, particularly the common law banking systems

4assess the importance of the quality of a country’s broader political and institutional framework for the development of an efficient, strong and honest financial market.

## General Transferable Skills

1. When presented with a set of facts, a student shall be able to do the following:

1. 1 state correctly the legal issues which arise from those facts;

1. 2 state correctly the relevant rules and the law for resolving those issues;

1. 3 cite accurately the relevant legal authorities to support the statement;

1. 4 state any legal distinctions between the rules stated and the facts given;

1. 5 apply the law to resolve those issues correctly and relevantly;

2. When presented with a question or statement containing a value judgement on an area of law, a student shall be able to:

2. 1 state correctly the rules and the law which are pertinent to evaluating the proposition contained in the question or statement;

2. 2 state relevant arguments for and against the proposition in an unbiased

manner;

2. 3 cite correctly the legal authorities and scholarly opinions which support or refute those arguments;

2. 4 assess accurately the strengths and weaknesses of those arguments;

2. 5 state a reasoned conclusion on those arguments.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

if !supportLists?·endif?acquire an awareness of the strengths and weaknesses of criminal law as a means of regulating society in the context of competing and conflicting interests;

if !supportLists?·endif?demonstrate a critical understanding of the principles that form the foundation of the structure and operations of the criminal justice system;

if !supportLists?·endif?critically analyse these principles in terms of the past, present and future of Hong Kong’s criminal justice system; and

if !supportLists?·endif?conduct research and formulate arguments concerning various aspects of crime and criminal justice.

The course has two learning outcomes. The first learning outcome is the ability to think critically about the economic and political criteria that inform PTAs and reflect on the practice of PTAs in the context of the WTO. The second learning outcome is the ability to express the laws that regulate PTAs into applicable principles.

The course has other, more general, learning outcomes. They include the ability:

·to demonstrate an accurate, extensive, and critical knowledge of the values, laws, and procedures appropriate to the topic;

·to apply that knowledge to the solution of theoretical and practical problems;

·to evaluate the theories and practices applicable to the solution of those problems by reference to appropriate sources;

·to identify the arguments of those sources with precision;

·to demonstrate evidence of independent (print and online) research, critical assessment, development of (persuasive and meaningful) argument, comprehensive citation, clear prose, and time management to an acceptable standard at LLB level;

·to complete assessment tasks, meet deadlines for the completion of those tasks, and take opportunities for feedback upon completion of those tasks; and,

·to participate effectively and thoughtfully as a member of a group (with respect to the classes) and as an individual (with respect to the assessment tasks).

courses.recommended_readings:
The course has two core textbooks.

The first core textbook is: Raj Bhala, *International Trade Law: Interdisciplinary Theory and Practice* (3rd ed, LexisNexis, 2008).

The second core textbook is: Gonzalo Villalta Puig, *Economic Relations between Australia and the European Union: Law and Policy* (Kluwer Law International, 2014).

Other relevant books are:

- Lorand Bartels and Federico Ortino (eds), *Regional Trade Agreements and the WTO Legal System* (Oxford University Press, 2006);

- Kyle W Bagwell and Petros C Mavroidis (eds), *Preferential Trade Agreements: A Law and Economics Analysis* (Cambridge University Press, 2011);

- Jagdish Bhagwati, Pravin Krishna and Arvind Panagariya (eds), *Trading Blocs: Alternative Approaches to Analyzing Preferential Trade Agreements* (MIT Press, 1999);

- Caroline Freund (ed), *The WTO and Reciprocal Preferential Trading Agreements: Critical Perspectives on the Global Trading System and the WTO* (Edward Elgar, 2007);

- David Gantz, *Regional Trade Agreements: Law, Policy and Practice* (Carolina Academic Press, 2009);

- Simon Lester and Bryan Mercurio, *Bilateral and Regional Trade Agreements: Case Studies* (Cambridge University Press, 2009);

- James Mathis, *Regional Trade Agreements in the GATT/WTO: Article XXIV and the International Trade Requirement* (Asser Press, 2002).

Periodicals of relevance include:

- *Journal of International Economic Law*;

- *Journal of World Trade*;

- *World Trade Review*;

- *Legal Issues of Economic Integration*;

- *International Trade Law & Regulation*;

- *Manchester Journal of International Economic Law*;

- *Journal of International Trade Law and Policy*; and

- *International and Comparative Law Quarterly*.

The Regional Trade Agreements Gateway of the World Trade Organization is an excellent online resource: http://www.wto.org/english/tratop\_e/region\_e/region\_e.htm.

Students have access to a Blackboard site for the course, which serves as a repository for course materials and notices: http://elearn.cuhk.edu.hk.

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of this course, students will be able to:

* Grasp the primary rules and principles of PRC contract law;
* Situate changes in PRC contract law in the context of an evolving market economy;
* Appreciate differences between concepts and doctrines in PRC contract law and those of other legal traditions including common law jurisdictions such as Hong Kong;
* Analyze factual situations in order to identify relevant issues of PRC contract law;
* Develop critical thinking, problem solving, written presentation, oral argumentation and teamwork skills.

Students will:

* gain an understanding of the organisations, basic themes, laws, rules and regulations relating to international economic law;
* understand the role of government, the private sector and international organisations in economic development;
* receive information through a comparative perspective and be able to identify and discuss the inter-disciplinary and overlapping nature of international economic law;
* be able to critically analyse the functions and workings of each of the prongs of international economic law; and
* receive the necessary context to allow for engagement in international economic law practice in both public and private international law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

- understand legal and regulatory framework of international air transport

- appreciate the complexity of airline business operations;
- identify the relevant legal principles in relation to airline business;
- understand the law and relationship between business operation of airlines, political consideration of a government, influence of the economy and intense competition; and

- demonstrate an awareness of strategies to mitigate exposure to legal liability.

By the end of this course, you should be able to:

- Discuss some of the major issues in the field of law and literature;
- Argue whether literature enhances our understanding of the law and, if so, in what ways it accomplishes this;
- Explore similarities law shares with literature;
- Understand how storytelling techniques can enhance our legal practice; and

- Reflect on the relation of the "real" and "fictional" aspects of the lives we live as lawyers.

- This course should also significantly enhance your critical reading skills and your ability to express yourself effectively orally and in writing using plain English. The ability to read critically and communicate effectively are two of the most important skills required to practice law successfully in any capacity.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• Understand and evaluate the impact of legal technologies on the future of the legal profession;
• Have a general understanding of the technical aspects of legal technologies;
• Conceptualize logical frameworks of legal thinking and decision-making and how these translate into machine protocols;
• Identify the point at which man and machine can “most productively meet” and place themselves there;
• Describe and critically assess the main forms of legal technologies and their value for legal work;
• Demonstrate a thorough understanding of the application of legal technologies in particular legal fields;
• Critically assess the implications of legal technologies from the rule of law and legal ethics point of view.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• Have knowledge of the fundamental aspects of AI;
• Apply knowledge of AI to specific legal practices and scenarios;
• Think analytically and philosophically about legal issues applied to AI;
• Assess AI’s impact on the future direction of law & the legal profession.

By the end of this course, students will:
o understand the theoretical and practical impact of and different ways how to achieve legal harmonization and unification;
o have knowledge of the mechanisms as well as related legal issues of international sales transactions;
o be able to appreciate the development of the CISG and its predecessors in the past, present and future;
o be in a position to appraise the value of the CISG with a special emphasis on Hong Kong’s legal system, China’s Belt & Road Initiative and the Greater Bay Area;
o have developed an understanding of the detailed provisions of the CISG and their practical implications;
o have the capacity to formulate convincing arguments relating to any theoretical and practical aspect of the CISG;
o have developed basic structuring and drafting skills relating to international sales transactions which are governed by or related to the CISG.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• possess a critical, thorough understanding of the regulatory challenges associated with the Digital Age in general and the platform economy in particular;
• competently advise companies, platform users and workers on how best to comply with the law and exercise their legal rights;
• reflect critically on how the current legal framework can address the new ‘digitalized’ reality, and propose normative solutions where necessary;
• recognize and rationalize the most important cases and investigations relating to the digital economy, and apply that knowledge to new practical scenarios;
• grasp the need to balance the innovative potential of the digital economy with the risks associated with the power amassed by platform ecosystems and their social responsibility;
• improve oral and written communications skills by competently constructing legal arguments, and conducting legal research.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• Discuss and critically evaluate the concepts of property and ownership;
• Discuss and critically evaluate the basic principles of law which apply to the ownership and transfer of ownership of property;
• Demonstrate an understanding of some specific doctrines and principles of property holding and transfer applicable in Hong Kong;
• Apply this understanding to problem scenarios involving property transactions and disputes over property.

By the end of this course, you will be able to:

* Demonstrate a sound understanding of international legal doctrines discussed in the class and formulate legal arguments on their basis;
* Understand the nature of international law and be able to theorise as to its viability as a law form;
* Distinguish between international law and municipal law and understand the several philosophies relating to this relationship;
* Comprehend the role of international law in international politics and governance;
* Conduct basic research on international law.

