courses.course_syllabus:
LAWS4291 Course Syllabus

The course comprises 2 parts:

1. Seminar series;

2. Casework.

* Seminar series*

Students will attend, and actively participate in, a series of seminars. These seminars will provide instruction on asylum and refugee law in Hong Kong and will also serve to prepare students for their casework. Attendance at these seminars is compulsory.

* Casework*

Students will undertake casework assigned to them by Barnes & Daly Solicitors at the start of the term. These students will be supervised by the firm’s partners and associates. The precise nature of the pro bono work that students undertake will vary and depend on the needs of the office. Students can expect to be assigned casework on any of the following areas:

1. CAT claims;

2. administrative law challenges to government policy and decisions;

3. Basic Law challenges concerning refugees’ fundamental rights;

4. judicial review applications concerning asylum seekers.

courses.learning_outcomes:
After taking this course, students should be able to:

1. Explain to a client or prospective client the basic principles of administrative law/judicial review;

2. Explain to a client or prospective client the remedies available to them for challenging government and legislative acts in Hong Kong;

3. Identify, analyze, research, and gather support related to the legal and factual issues of a claim;

4. Write a legal submission and/or legal brief;

5. Advocate on behalf of a hypothetical client in regard to a public interest issue;

6. Reflect critically on and take action to advance the theory and practice of a public interest law issue in Hong Kong, the development of their professional skills and ethics, the nature of the lawyer-client relationship, and the value of pro bono service to unmet legal needs in the community.

By the end of this course, students are able to

¨Understand the operation of environmental regulatory schemes in Hong Kong;

¨ Appreciate the roles and limits of judicial review, tort law and criminal law in environmental protection;

¨ Appreciate the cross-border and global nature of environmental problems and the role of bilateral and multilateral cooperation;

¨ Conduct legal research in both local and international environmental law;

¨ Apply the legal rules, doctrines and principles to solve environmental problems;

¨ Critically analyze and evaluate Hong Kong environmental law as they are; and

¨ Propose recommendations as to what the law should be to better protect the environment.

LAWS4311 Learning Outcomes

By the end of this course, students are able to

¨understand the operation of environmental regulatory schemes in China;

¨appreciate the function of civil, criminal and administrative laws in environmental protection;

¨conduct legal research in both Chinese and international environmental law;

¨apply the legal rules, doctrines and principles to solve environmental problems;

¨critically evaluate the roles of regulatory agencies, courts and NGOs in protecting the environment;

¨analyze cross-border and global environmental problems and evaluate bilateral and multilateral legal schemes on environmental protection;

¨critically evaluate and assess Chinese environmental law both on paper and in practice; and

¨propose law reform to improve the environmental legal regime in China.

By the end of the course, students should:

·have a critical understanding of competition law;

·be able to analyse current issues in competition law, both substantive and procedural;

·possess the capacity to explain the routes available to private parties in seeking remedies based on competition law;

·understand appeals procedures against public decisions on competition law;

·use research methods on competition law efficiently;

·be able to deconstruct and solve a hypothetical legal problem related to competition law;

·competently construct written and oral legal arguments.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

·show a critical understanding of competing philosophical accounts of privacy and understand their connection to theories of the law more generally;

· demonstrate core knowledge of the legal frameworks that govern the collection, use, and disclosure of personal information in both Hong Kong and other jurisdictions;

·identify weaknesses in existing laws and policies in the context of new problems in the area of personal privacy, and be able to propose logical and rational solutions;

·synthesize significant amounts of information and present it in a cohesive manner;

·critically assess the arguments of both peers and those found in the relevant literature;

·comfortably defend a particular interpretation of law or policy orally;

·write clearly, logically and accurately;

· conduct intensive legal research in an area of interest and produce an original essay of high quality.

By the end of this course, students should be able to:

* Understand the problems in protecting different types of art, antiquities and cultural heritage;
* Understand the use of the common law to protect art, antiquities and cultural heritage;
* Critically analyze the protection of art, antiquities and cultural heritage in Hong Kong;
* Evaluate Hong Kong’s position in the international trade in art, antiquities and cultural heritage.

The aim is that by the end of the course students will:

* Possess substantive knowledge of the guiding principles and indicative detail of the Hong Kong law of unjust enrichment;
* Develop their skills of critical analysis and creative thought;
* Develop their skills of coherent argument and clear communication;
* Understand the place of unjust enrichment in the law of obligations and its practical use.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

* Understand better the variety of roles law can play and has played in society;
* Be familiar with an extensive range of historical and theoretical scholarship relating to law and colonialism;
* Be able to assess and critique the merits and weaknesses of different scholarly arguments and contentions;
* Develop a critical, historically-informed approach to contemporary legal structures;
* Develop original reflections on law’s history and function.

By the end of this course, you will be able to:

• demonstrate a critical understanding of the technology and the causes of action;
• describe the fundamental principles of copyright applied to this technology;
• describe international context of copyright and information technology; and
• conduct relevant legal research, write basic advice documents.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• have a critical understanding of merger control regimes;
• identify the circumstances under which a relevant merger exists, and to determine the assignation of jurisdiction;
• analyse current issues in merger control, both substantive and procedural;
• use research methods on merger control law efficiently;
• deconstruct and solve a hypothetical legal problem related to merger control;
• construct written and oral legal arguments.

By the end of this course, students should:

* possess a critical understanding of the rules, policies, and principles of compliance;
* appreciate the role of compliance processes in the management of risk;
* understand the relationship between compliance, corporate governance and corporate culture;
* be able to apply legal and regulatory requirements to the design and implementation of an effective compliance program;
* be able to evaluate, and advise on, the impact of compliance programs and compliance failures in regulatory and criminal proceedings.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the basics of electronic digital technology;
• understand how the use of electronic digital technology by lawyers is changing the practice of law;
• understand how the law affects electronic digital technology;
• understand how the use of electronic digital technology in many aspects of our lives is changing or may have to change law;
• research for the course using various legal research tools (online and otherwise);
• critically evaluate issues arising from the use of electronic digital technology, taking into account legal and non-legal issues (including social and economic issues);
• give basic advice on issues that arise from the use of electronic digital technology.

This course is designed to give students the basic legal skills and professional knowledge needed for the PCLL and for professional practice, including:

• to develop a strong sense of ethics and professional responsibilities and to be familiar with the ethical requirements of the professions;
• to be able to recognise and resolve ethical dilemmas and appreciate ethical formation;
• to develop an understanding of the nature and regulation of the legal profession
• to acquire a basic understanding of financial statements;
• to be able to apply the Solicitors’ Accounts Rules to simple transactions; and
• to use process problem solving skills.

This course is designed to enable you to:
• represent a vendor and the vendor’s bank and conduct a sale of a residential flat or house and a discharge from mortgage;
• represent a purchaser and the purchaser’s bank and conduct a purchase of a residential flat or house and a mortgage to finance the purchase;
• represent a landlord or a tenant and complete a lease of a residential flat;
• represent a testator and draft a will;
• represent the personal representatives of a person who has died testate or intestate, advise on succession and the administration and distribution of their estate; and
• research and advise in the context of these matters.

By the end of the course, students should be able to distinguish different forms of security, of loan agreements, the common terms therein, the terms specific to particular industries, and to be able to draft an appropriate document.

Matters to be discussed in class include, and therefore should enable the student to:
• identify the types of security interests relevant to lending and finance in Hong Kong;
• distinguish between real securities and quasi-securities;
• understand the benefit of a security – and how to draft where perfection of a security is not possible;
• review various forms of loan agreements in Hong Kong;
• understand the different types of services provided by the different types of banks operating in the Hong Kong banking market;
• understand the principal terms of the most common forms of loan facilities in use in the Hong Kong banking market; and
• prepare a working manual of matters relevant to the financial markets seat in the office.

On successful completion of the course, you will be able to:-
• have a broad understanding of the substantive law and rules relevant to Hong Kong’s corporate finance regime;
• have a sound understanding of the procedures involved in a main board listing (including planning, application and documentation) and major compliance matters;
• develop practical skills and experience in drafting, amending, and editing agreements/documents involved in the relevant transactions; and
• be able to assist in the conduct of the relevant corporate transactions and advise on the practical and commercial implications of the documentation involved in the relevant transactions.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• dissect and digest a set of instructions so that the client can be advised on the issues on which he seeks advice
• undertake focused legal research in order to produce legal opinions which are supported by legal authority as appropriate;
• analyse the legal issues, identifying the relevant law, apply it to the facts and reach a clear conclusion;
• plan and draft a clearly structured and well written legal opinion or advice.

This course is offered in Term 2 of the PCLL programme as an elective. It is designed to enable students to:-
• acquire legal knowledge on the latest developments in China’s foreign investment regime;
• gain a sound understanding of the approval and setting up procedures relevant to commercial transactions involving foreign investors in China;
• develop their legal knowledge and practical skills acquired from Stage 1 of the PCLL programme and apply the same to China’s specific legal, economic, social and political contexts;
• advise on various commercial and cross-border issues commonly encountered by foreign investors in China;
• conduct due diligence and draft agreements relating to the specific commercial transactions covered by this course.

This course is designed to enable students to:-
• use Chinese language as the medium of communication to represent and advise clients in commercial transactions;
• conduct commercial transactions by taking instructions and drafting documents in Chinese;
• understand the rules and techniques on the proper use of Chinese language for legal writing;
• understand the practical implications and limitations of using English precedents to draft documents in Chinese; and
• develop practical Chinese drafting skills and experience in drafting, amending, and editing documents to achieve consistency and accuracy.

This course is designed to enable students to:-
• represent and advise clients in commercial transactions;
• conduct commercial transactions by taking instructions and drafting documents setting out the intention of the parties;
• conduct research on specific technical areas in commercial transactions;
• understand the practical and commercial implications of the documents involved in the transaction;
• negotiate the terms of documents on behalf of a client;
• develop practical skills and experience in drafting amending, and editing documents to achieve consistency and accuracy; and
• settle agreements/documents and take steps to complete a transaction.

Throughout this course students will learn by practice and experience and develop a range of professional, practical and personal skills.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

• communicate at an advanced level, both verbally and in writing;
• obtain and act upon clients' instructions and provide practical solutions for clients' objectives and problems;
• organize and manage your work appropriately, and to meet deadlines;
• research and learn independently;
• demonstrate strategic and critical thinking in your professional work; and
• identify professional ethical issues which may arise in practice and deal with them professionally.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• discuss the fundamental aspects of a legal system;
• identify the main categories of law;
• describe the historical development of the Hong Kong legal system;
• describe and critique legal institutions in Hong Kong;
• identify and describe key legal personnel in Hong Kong;
• discuss the sources of Hong Kong law;
• explain key legal processes and procedures in Hong Kong;
• distinguish different concepts of the rule of law; and
• evaluate the operation of the rule of law in Hong Kong.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• provide a correct descriptive account of the theories covered in the course;
• engage in critical analysis of those theories;
• develop an original argument relating those theories to wider questions in an intelligent manner;
• be comfortable working with abstract concepts and philosophical first principles.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the importance of lawyers in society based upon the rule of law;
• understand how law can be used to benefit vulnerable groups in society such as children, prisoners, domestic workers, victims of domestic violence;
• be able to work with selected groups in society so as to identify their needs vis-à-vis the legal system;
• be able to identify shortcomings in the law and legal process in terms of the needs of vulnerable groups in society;
• understand the importance of public interest litigation and how it differs from normal litigation.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• express themselves clearly, logically and coherently using plain language;
• plan, write, edit and revise their work and think like a writer;
• write texts that they will write during their legal studies including case notes, summaries, memoranda of law or advice, answers to problem questions, answers to examination questions, essays and papers;
• format their writing appropriately for the task;
• write persuasively;
• develop style;
• learn by doing, and giving and receiving feedback;
• identify, find and read primary and secondary sources of law;
• use the major commercial legal databases;
• be able to develop a research question, conduct research into current law, the evolution of law, the impact of the law and criticism and reform of the law and think like a researcher;
• be familiar with style guides and cite authorities accurately and consistently;
• think critically and creatively.

Upon successful completion of this course students will be able:

• to understand the practical significance and instrumentality of comparative law;
• to explain how various legal systems are adapting to change;
• to assess critically traditional concepts of comparative law and to develop alternative options;
• to apply comparative law methodology in a practical context;
• to conduct research in relation to the topics addressed by the course.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the role and characteristics of a partnership in Hong Kong law;
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the role and characteristics of a private limited liability company;
• describe the structure and formal arrangements of a Hong Kong private limited liability company with a particular emphasis on majority rule and the constitutional documents;
• describe the different sources of Hong Kong law for the incorporation and management of a company and the division of powers between the Board of Directors and the shareholders in general meeting;
• explain the different ways that the company’s constitution can be altered and the significance of the Memorandum and Articles of Association;
• demonstrate an understanding of the meaning of “shares” in company law and the different ways that shares can be allocated and transferred;
• explain the law relating to the appointment ,tenure and removal of directors and directors’ duties;
• demonstrate an understanding of the meaning of corporate personality, corporate authority and agency problems in company law;
• explore shareholder rights and remedies and the legal issues relevant to company meetings and shareholder resolutions;
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the role and characteristics of share capital and class rights in a private limited liability company;
• describe the meaning and characteristics of debt and equity capital in a private limited liability company;
• demonstrate an understanding of the law relating to groups of companies;
• explain the law relating to section 168A petitions and the law on statutory derivative actions and minority shareholders’ rights generally;
• demonstrate an understanding of the law relating to fixed and floating charges;
• demonstrate an understanding of the law relating to Romalpa clauses, the doctrine of relation back and fraudulent preference as they relate to the supply of credit to a company;
• demonstrate an understanding of insolvency law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• conduct research on civil procedural topics;
• demonstrate an understanding of pre-action considerations, including time limitation and legal aid;
• identify the jurisdiction of the courts in civil actions;
• demonstrate a sound and practical understanding of the civil justice process;
• identify the appropriate steps to be taken before the commencement of an action, during the conduct of an action, in preparation for and during the trial and post-trial.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

• understand the role of the judge and the jury in relation to the admissibility/assessment of evidence;
• ascertain who bears the burden of proof in respect of any given case or issue in a case, and explain to what standard facts must be proved in various civil and criminal contexts;
• understand how rules governing the admissibility of evidence work in practice;
• place the rules of evidence within their wider historical, social and psychological context;
• solve problem questions which require research into, understanding and application of the main rules of evidence governing proof of facts in criminal and civil trials.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• have a practical understanding of the rules of criminal procedure;
• understand the obligations as a criminal practitioner to the client, the court, the professional body, and the community;
• be able to advise on all aspects of the criminal process from arrest to appeal.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the meaning of “constitutional law” and the differences between constitutional and administrative law;
• describe the fundamental principles of constitutional law;
• demonstrate an understanding of the differences and interrelationship of constitutional and administrative in the context of the political and administrative system in Hong Kong;
• describe the Basic Law and its relationship to international law and the constitutional system of the People’s republic of China;
• demonstrate an understanding of selected rights and freedoms of residents of Hong Kong in the context of the Basic Law;
• identify constitutional issues and the role of law and government;
• describe the relationship of the Basic Law and the Hong Kong court system;
• conduct basic legal research and make formal presentations to the class.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical overview of conveyancing transactions under deeds and title registration systems and the economic importance of the integrity of the systems;
• demonstrate a sound understanding of the basic principles and legal rules of conveyancing law;
• read legal documents;
• identify facts and issues and apply the principles and rules to resolve legal problems;
• conduct research and formulate legal arguments;
• learn without prior instruction; and
• write clearly, logically and accurately.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of commercial law;
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the law relating to consumer protection in Hong Kong law, including The Sale of Goods Ordinance, the Moneylenders Ordinance and the Control of Exemption Clauses Ordinance;
• describe specific commercial transactions from the perspective of the supplier and creditor;
• demonstrate an understanding of the different types of choses in action and how they may be assigned;
• explain significant aspects of security interests and how they are used in commercial law in Hong Kong;
• explain the relevance of bills of exchange, negotiable instruments and aspects of banking law in commercial law;
• explain the relevant law relating to personal property, interests in personal property and rights of possession;
• explain the relevance of the law relating to the nemo dat rule, exceptions to the rule and the law on gifts and conditional gifts in the commercial law context;
• demonstrate an understanding of bankruptcy law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• outline the history of the development of equity;
• describe the role, function, strengths and limitations of equity;
• explain the history, development, role and function of the trust;
• summarise and explain key provisions of the law governing trusts in Hong Kong;
• provide basic legal advice in the area of equity and trusts;
• describe the remedies developed by equity;
• give an educated opinion of the future of equity;
• evaluate the trust as it functions in Hong Kong;
• appreciate the role that trust play in modern society.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the development of land law and its economic and social importance;
• develop awareness of the development of land law in other common law jurisdictions;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of the principles and legal rules of land law;
• understand in outline how the principles and legal rules apply to transactions involving land;
• identify facts and issues and apply the principles and rules to resolve legal problems;
• conduct legal research and formulate arguments; and
• write clearly, logically and accurately.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the administrative law’s place in society in relation to other methods of economic and social co-ordination;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of the main legal rules and principles of administrative law;
• identify legal problems involving those rules and principles;
• demonstrate an ability to apply the main rules and principles of administrative law to formulate possible solutions to factual problems;
• conduct basic legal research, and formulate oral arguments concerning the rules and principles of administrative law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the meaning of contracts and their place in society in relation to other methods of economic and social co-ordination;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of the main legal rules and principles of contract;
• identify legal problems involving those rules and principles;
• demonstrate an ability to apply the main rules and principles of contract to formulate possible solutions to factual problems, and
• conduct basic legal research and formulate oral arguments concerning the rules and principles of contract.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the meaning of crime and its place in society in relation to other methods of regulation and social control;
• describe the fundamental principles of criminal liability;
• describe selected criminal offences, their structure, basis and operational basis;
• identify and solve criminal problems, and
• conduct basic legal research and make formal presentations to the class.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the meaning of torts and their place in society in relation to other methods of economic and social co-ordination;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of the main legal rules and principles of tort;
• identify legal problems involving those rules and principles;
• demonstrate an ability to apply the main rules and principles of tort to formulate possible solutions to factual problems, and
• conduct basic legal research and formulate oral arguments concerning the rules and principles of tort.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• Discuss and critically evaluate the concepts of property and ownership;
• Discuss and critically evaluate the basic principles of law which apply to the ownership and transfer of ownership of property;
• Demonstrate an understanding of some specific doctrines and principles of property holding and transfer applicable in Hong Kong;
• Apply this understanding to problem scenarios involving property transactions and disputes over property.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• explain the essential regulatory differences between public listed and private companies in Hong Kong law;
• demonstrate a critical understanding of issues in company law reform from the perspective of public listed and private companies in Hong Kong;
• demonstrate an understanding of the role of the Board of Directors in a public listed Hong Kong company;
• demonstrate an understanding of the Listing Rules and the role of the Independent Non-Executive Director in public listed companies;
• describe the regulatory framework of financial markets in Hong Kong for listed companies;
• describe the structure and significance of The Securities and Futures Ordinance;
• demonstrate an understanding of the role of the Hong Kong regulators in Hong Kong as a major international financial centre concept of share capital;
• demonstrate an understanding of the concept of capital and the capital maintenance rules;
• describe the current issues in debt and equity financing for private and public companies in the context of current company law reform;
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the law relating to floating charges in the context of current law reform;
• explain the role of the Independent Non-Executive Director;
• explain the underlying issues in groups of companies and the parent /subsidiary relationship;
• explain the underlying issues in corporate governance in the context of Hong Kong company directors and the criminalization of the regulatory system.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the meaning of contracts and their place in society in relation to other methods of economic and social co-ordination;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of some of the more advanced legal rules and principles of contract;
• identify legal problems involving those rules and principles;
• demonstrate an ability to apply the main rules and principles of contract to formulate possible solutions to factual problems; and
• conduct basic legal research and formulate oral arguments concerning the rules and principles of contract.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the meaning of crime and its place in society in relation to other methods of regulation and social control;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of some of the more advanced legal rules and principles of criminal liability;
• describe selected criminal offences, their structure, basis and operational basis;
• identify and solve criminal problems, and
• conduct basic legal research and make formal presentations to the class.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• describe the role, function, strengths and limitation of equity;
• summarise and explain advanced aspects of the law governing trusts in Hong Kong;
• provide advanced legal advice in the area of equity and trusts;
• describe to an advanced level of complexity the remedies developed by equity;
• give an educated opinion of the future of equity;
• evaluate to an advanced level the trusts as it functions in Hong Kong;
• demonstrate an advanced appreciation the role that trusts play in modern society.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the development of land law and its economic and social importance;
• develop awareness of the development of land law in other common law jurisdictions;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of the more advanced principles and legal rules of land law;
• understand in depth how the principles and legal rules apply to transactions involving land;
• identify facts and issues and apply the principles and rules to resolve more complex legal problems;
• conduct legal research and formulate arguments; and
• write clearly, logically and accurately.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of international law and its place in international society in relation to other methods of political, economic and social co-ordination;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of the main legal rules and principles of international law;
• identify legal problems involving those rules and principles;
• demonstrate an ability to apply the main rules and principles of international law to formulate possible solutions to factual problems; and
• conduct basic legal research, and formulate oral arguments concerning the rules and principles of international law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the fundamental structure and principles of Australian constitutional law;
• understand the Australian constitution in its relationship to international law;
• demonstrate an understanding of Australian federal executive, legislative and judicial powers and the
separation between them;
• demonstrate an understanding of the relationship between the Australian federal and state constitutions;
• conduct basic legal research in relation to Australian constitutional issues.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the fundamental structure and principles of Canadian constitutional law;
• understand the Canadian constitution in its relationship to international law;
• demonstrate an understanding of Canadian federal executive, legislative and judicial powers and the
separation between them;
• demonstrate an understanding of the relationship between the Canadian federal and provincial constitutions;
• conduct basic legal research in relation to Canadian constitutional issues.

By the end of the course, students should have:
• awareness of the key concepts of conflict of laws with particular reference to domicile, renvoi, classification, connecting factors, choice of jurisdiction, choice of law and recognition and enforcement of foreign judgments. Also to have awareness as to how Hong Kong’s principles of Conflict of Laws differ from the European and Mainland rules;
• understanding as to how these concepts apply in selected areas such as in contract law, tort, family law, property law and succession. Also to have an understanding of the importance of Conflict of Laws in practice;
• facility in identifying Conflict of Laws issues and correctly applying the relevant law. Also to have the facility to be able to evaluate the strength and weaknesses of the existing law and to formulate constructive views as to how the existing law could be improved.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• describe and demonstrate the skills involved in effective in interviewing and counseling;
• outline various models of legal interviewing and counseling (e.g. traditional, client-centred);
• discuss the strengths and weaknesses of each model, incorporating recent research findings;
• describe problems that are commonly encountered in interviews of a sensitive nature (which raise issues of age, gender / sexuality / ethnicity, ace, capacity);
• explain strategies and techniques that an be employed to deal with clients in difficult interview and counseling scenarios;
• work effectively with others in teams and in groups;
• write client interview and counseling scenarios, and
• conduct an effective legal interview and counseling session with a client.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• identify and understand the many forms of dispute resolution that are now available and used widely by lawyers throughout the world;
• exhibit skills of negotiation, mediation and arbitration;
• understand the advantages and disadvantages of each method of dispute resolution;
• understand the nature of human disputes and the ole of various formal and informal methods in resolving them.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the historical and philosophical foundations of Western constitutional traditions;
• appreciate the impact of the Western constitutional traditions on constitutionalism in non-Western societies;
• understand the nature of alternatives to constitutional government and the rule of law;
• appreciate the variety of means by which effect is given to fundamental constitutional values across different jurisdictions;
• understand the strengths and weaknesses in a variety of constitutional arrangements in giving effect to the values represented in constitutionalism;
• acquire a deeper understanding of Hong Kong’s constitutional order by comparing it to other jurisdictions.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• identify the legal principles relevant to the regulation of the environment;
• understand their role in treaty, customary, soft, statutory and case law;
• through suitable legal interpretation techniques, demonstrate an ability to apply the principles to environmental law problems in Hong Kong;
• conduct legal research, formulate oral and written arguments based on the above.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the laws, rules, normative and institutional framework within which human rights operate;
• understand the function of different international and domestic bodies and organizations in defining and enforcing human rights norms;
• understand the interaction of legal and non-legal issues that inform discussion and deliberations on human rights; and
• formulate and evaluate their own views on the above.

By the end of this course, students should be able to:
• know the substance and major issues of the field of law and literature;
• tell in what ways literature enhances our understanding of the law;
• identify epistemological and methodological similarities law shares with literature;
• explore what role rhetoric and style can play in the drafting of legal documents; and
• reflect over the relation of the "real" and "fictional" aspects of the lives we live as lawyers.

Students coming out of this course will be equipped with a general knowledge of:
• workings of the common law system and history governing employment relationships;
• in depth understanding of the Employment Ordinance and how it varies standard contract theory;
• an understanding of the industrial accident / employee compensation area;
• an overview of discrimination law - how this affects employers’ practices, hiring, and potential remedies.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• discuss and analyse the views of leading practitioners, judiciary and academics working in the area of judicial review;
• demonstrate an understanding of judicial review and contemporary issues relating to judicial review;
• identify and formulate an advanced research question pertaining to the field of judicial review; and
• carry out the research necessary to answer the research question and present that answer in a coherent, analytical and sufficiently sophisticated manner.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• analyse a given fact situation to identify the legal issues;
• research the law in order to formulate a legal strategy and argument;
• demonstrate an ability to formulate possible solutions to factual problems;
• draft a memorandum for appellant and respondent in proper form and language;
• read and analyse an appellant and respondent memorandum in order to formulate arguments and draft a memorandum in response;
• demonstrate oral advocacy skills including the organization and presentation of legal arguments, responding to questions from the bench, and persuasive summation;
• manage argument timing;
• master trial procedure and etiquette;
• work effectively as one of a two-person professional legal team.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• communicate with a prospective client and a client in a professional manner, including through the use of an interpreter;
• explain the caseworker-client relationship, confidentiality and other ethical concerns;
• explain the role of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), the role of HKRAC and the UNHCR’s refugee status determination process;
• explain the law and legal concepts in layman’s terms, including the definition of refugee in the 1951 Convention and the 1967 Protocol Relating to the Status of Refugees;
• interview a claimant, including one with particular vulnerabilities, to ascertain the facts relevant to the legal claim in an ethical and effective manner;
• write a detailed intake report and case summary;
• identify and analyze the legal and factual issues related to a claim;
• gather evidence and conduct legal and fact-based research related to a claim;
• write a formal assessment of the merits of a claim;
• prepare a formal client testimony. \*
\* Not all Clinic participants will prepare a formal client testimony.
This will depend on the availability of clients and cases as well as each student’s progress and level of expertise, engagement and profession

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• appreciate the theory and practice of mediation and its benefits;
• describe the theory and practice associated with the different stages of a mediation process;
• identify and understand the different forms of mediation;
• understand the salient features of mediation;
• appreciate cultural differences and their impact on a mediation process;
• have gained experience working in a group as part of a role play;
• appreciate the different perspectives of possible stakeholders involved in a mediation process;
• be able to use basic negotiating and mediation techniques in a realistic setting.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand and explain fundamental concepts of income taxation and transaction-based taxation;
• identify Hong Kong tax issues and outcomes in a wide variety of fact patterns;
• describe the development of Hong Kong’s tax system and the most important tax policy issues currently facing the Hong Kong government;
• appreciate the competing policy factors affecting tax practice and administration;
• advocate possible tax law reform measures from a policy perspective.

Through class work, reading and discussions students will:
• understand a wide range of contemporary issues in tort law which are challenging established principles of tort law;
• learn about different solutions adopted in various jurisdictions to deal with a variety of issues in tort law;
• develop reading, research, problem solving, writing and oral communication skills.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the various causes of action which comprise intellectual property;
• describe the fundamental principles of intellectual property;
• describe international context of intellectual property law;
• conduct basic legal research.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• critically understand the law relevant to the topics covered in the subject;
• make use of policy statement, practice notes, guidance notes, issues by the regulatory bodies when assessing the state of the law;
• identify and analyze the legal issues that typically arise in securities market transactions;
• evaluate legal rules and legal theories in this area.

By the end of this course, students will have developed:
• their critical faculties by evaluating the rules, policies, and principles of insurance law;
• their analytical faculties by identifying and resolving legal arguments arising out of insurance law disputes;
• their understanding of the insurance contract, particularly its terms which relate to the obligations borne by the insured once the risk insured against occurs and a claim is lodged with the underwriters.

• critical awareness of the scale and nature of corporate crime; the legal, social, and commercial factors that are relevant in defining and identifying such crime; the legal policy behind the regulatory responses to corporate crime, the principles of corporate social responsibility;
• postgraduate understanding in the issues of legal theory that apply to corporate liability, legal and criminological reasoning about the nature and causes of corporate crime, corporate penological theory, the impact on companies and on society of the doctrine of corporate social responsibility;
• facility in integrating postgraduate knowledge from the fields of law, criminology, and social and organizational science in relation to corporate conduct; applying legal, social, and ethical analyses to corporate behaviour, and in discussing and critically evaluating issues of corporate social responsibility; critically transferring analyses from one jurisdiction to another.

This Course aims to address the following knowledge and skills. By the end of the course, students should have:
• awareness of the subject of construction law as both a discipline and legal practice area;
• understanding of the historical, legal, contractual and theoretical frameworks for the subject;
• facility in the preparation of legal advice in relation to the planning and delivery of and dispute resolution on a construction project.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of international law and its place in international society in relation to other methods of political, economic and social co-ordination;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of the legal rules and principles of international law as they relate to the substantive areas of law covered in the syllabus;
• identify legal problems involving those rules and principles;
• demonstrate an ability to apply the main rules and principles of international law to formulate possible solutions to factual problems; and
• conduct basic legal research, and formulate oral arguments concerning the rules and principles of international law as they relate to the substantive areas of law covered in the syllabus.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

• appreciate the complexity of airline business operations;
• identify and understand the relevant legal principles in relation to each of the selected core aspects of airline business operation;
• understand the law and relationship between business operation of airlines, political consideration of a government, influence of the economy and intense competition; and
• demonstrate an awareness of strategies to mitigate exposure to legal liability.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• Understand the issues of corporate insolvency;
• Possess substantive knowledge of the guiding principles and indicative detail of corporate insolvency law;
• Develop their skills of critical analysis and creative thought;
• Develop their skills of coherent argument and clear communication.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• show a critical understanding of competing philosophical accounts of privacy and understand their connection to theories of the law more generally;
• demonstrate core knowledge of the legal frameworks that govern the collection, use, and disclosure of personal information in both Hong Kong and other jurisdictions;
• identify weaknesses in existing laws and policies in the context of new problems in the area of personal privacy, and be able to propose logical and rational solutions;
• synthesize significant amounts of information and present it in a cohesive manner;
• critically assess the arguments of both peers and those found in the relevant literature;
• comfortably defend a particular interpretation of law or policy orally;
• write clearly, logically and accurately;
• conduct intensive legal research in an area of interest and produce an original essay of high quality.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• describe and unpack various ideas about ‘marriage’;
• to discuss the construction of the married couple and nuclear family and the role of the law in their definition and continuation;
• to describe the law of Hong Kong in relation to marriage, separation, divorce, nullity and maintenance;
• to outline trends in the resolution of financial disputes on divorce;
• to outline some of the international trends in matrimonial law;
• to describe the role that mediation has in transforming matrimonial law;
• to describe the way in which the law responds to / fails to respond to violence in the home;
• to explain how the law and legal processes often fail the victim of domestic violence;
• to conduct research on a selected topic in matrimonial law;
• have developed their ability to speak in class;
• have developed their ability to work in ad hoc groups in class;
• have developed their capacity for self-reflection.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• to describe and unpack various ideas about ‘the child’, ‘children’ and the legal status of children;
• to discuss the construction of the parent-child relationship and the role of the law in its definition and continuation including the concept of parental responsibility and the acquisition of parenthood by adoption;
• to describe the law of Hong Kong in relation to parenthood, adoption, maintenance of children, custody, child abuse and child protection, children’s rights and international law relating to children;
• to outline some of the international trends in child law;
• to describe the role that mediation has in transforming child dispute resolution;
• to describe the way in which the law responds to / fails to respond to violence against children;
• to explain how the law and legal processes attempt to give the child a voice in those proceedings and how this might be reformed to achieve greater representation of the child’s views;
• to analyse critically the key schools of thinking in the discourse on children’s rights.

After taking this course, students should be able to:
• Explain to a client or prospective client the basic principles of administrative law/judicial review;
• Explain to a client or prospective client the remedies available to them for challenging government and legislative acts in Hong Kong;
• Identify, analyze, research, and gather support related to the legal and factual issues of a claim;
• Write a legal submission and/or legal brief;
• Advocate on behalf of a hypothetical client in regard to a public interest issue;
• Reflect critically on and take action to advance the theory and practice of a public interest law issue in Hong Kong, the development of their professional skills and ethics, the nature of the lawyer-client relationship, and the value of pro bono service to unmet legal needs in the community.

The aim of the course is to give students a thorough grasp of the law of the sea, laying particular emphasis on the regime set out under the 1982 UN Convention on the Law the Sea and the various implementing agreements. It will focus predominantly on primary legal materials, enabling students to critically assess different kinds of documents, from the treaties and travaux preparatoires to the cases and judgments. As well as reading these materials, students will be expected to reflect on and discuss questions arising from them. By the end of the course, students should to be able to make well-informed arguments based on the various doctrinal approaches, policy-driven factors, and practical considerations discussed throughout.

In particular, students will gain a good working knowledge of:

• The main principles and concepts shaping the law of the sea;
• The legal frameworks governing the law of the sea;
• The functions of the international organisations regulating activities covered by law of the sea;
• The functions of the international bodies upholding the law of the sea in the event of disputes, and the relevant cases.

In addition, students will gain a solid grounding in:
• The general features of treaty-based and customary public international law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• Grasp a range of legal issues of particular significance to older persons in Hong Kong;
• Understand the social, economic, cultural, and political contexts within which elder law issues have emerged in Hong Kong and other ageing societies;
• Identify the ethical principles and values underpinning elder law issues;
• Critique the theoretical justifications of elder law as a specialized body of law and its relationship with other areas of law;
• Gain insights from a variety of disciplines (such as sociology, gerontology, psychology, bioethics, public health administration, economics, public policy) in relation to the legal issues affecting older persons as patients, clients, consumers, etc.;
• Demonstrate advanced problem solving, evaluative, communication, teamwork, and creative skills in applying acquired knowledge to case problems;
• Collect, analyze, evaluate, and synthesize relevant materials for undertaking advanced legal research;
• Identify appropriate legal resources to address the needs and concerns of older persons as well as their family members, friends, and/or caregivers.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the principles of taxation in Hong Kong and selected countries that have close economic ties with Hong Kong;
• explain how tax considerations affect the structure, location and nature of certain businesses and transactions;
• identify potential tax risks and suggest possible solutions;
• provide basic legal advice on Hong Kong tax law; and
• analyse policy considerations concerning the tax systems in Hong Kong and other countries.

By the end of this course, students will obtain the following skills in relation to facilitative mediation:

• communicate at an advanced level, both verbally and in writing, in relation to mediation and other ADR processes;
• obtain and act upon clients' instructions and provide practical ADR solutions to meet clients' objectives and problems;
• organize and manage their work appropriately, and to meet deadlines;
• research and learn independently;
• demonstrate strategic and critical thinking in their professional work; and
• identify professional ethical issues which may arise in Mediation practice and deal with them professionally and practically.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• Understand and evaluate the impact of legal technologies on the future of the legal profession;
• Have a general understanding of the technical aspects of legal technologies;
• Conceptualize logical frameworks of legal thinking and decision-making and how these translate into machine protocols;
• Identify the point at which man and machine can “most productively meet” and place themselves there;
• Describe and critically assess the main forms of legal technologies and their value for legal work;
• Demonstrate a thorough understanding of the application of legal technologies in particular legal fields;
• Critically assess the implications of legal technologies from the rule of law and legal ethics point of view.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the basics of electronic digital technology;
• understand how the use of electronic digital technology by lawyers is changing the
practice of law;
• understand how the law affects electronic digital technology;
• understand how the use of electronic digital technology in many aspects of our lives is
changing or may have to change law;
• research for the course using various legal research tools (online and otherwise);
• critically evaluate issues arising from the use of electronic digital technology, taking into
account legal and non-legal issues (including social and economic issues);
• give basic advice on issues that arise from the use of electronic digital technology.

By the end of this course, students will:
• have advanced understanding of the theoretical and practical impact of and different
ways how to achieve legal harmonization and unification;
• have comprehensive knowledge of the mechanisms as well as related legal issues of
international sales transactions;
• be able to appreciate comprehensively the development of the CISG and its predecessors
in the past, present and future;
• be well-positioned to appraise the value of the CISG with a special emphasis on Hong
Kong’s legal system, China’s Belt & Road Initiative and the Greater Bay Area;
• have developed a deep understanding of the detailed provisions of the CISG and their
practical implications;
• have the capacity to formulate striking arguments relating to any theoretical and
practical aspect of the CISG and to communicate these arguments in a convincing
manner;
• have developed advanced structuring and drafting skills relating to international sales
transactions which are governed by or related to the CISG.

By the end of this course, students should:

* possess a critical understanding of the rules, policies, and principles of compliance;
* understand and be ready to critically assess current debates about corporate reporting and monitoring obligations as a tool of policy implementation;
* appreciate the role of compliance processes in the management of risk;
* understand the relationship between compliance, corporate governance and corporate culture;
* be able to apply legal and regulatory requirements to the design and implementation of an effective compliance program;
* be able to evaluate, and advise on, the impact of compliance programs and compliance failures in regulatory and criminal proceedings.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the basic principles, methods, processes and institutions of law in contemporary China;
• understand the historical, social and cultural contexts in which Chinese law has evolved and operated, and understand the role of law in China’s social and economic development;
• apply the principles of Chinese law to practical situations and analyze current events in China from the legal perspective;
• conduct advanced research on Chinese law; and
• understand the differences and interface between the Mainland legal system and the Hong Kong legal system.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• gave a working knowledge of the major civil law doctrines and methods of China;
• demonstrate a broad understanding of the role and function of civil law in the contemporary Chinese society;
• be proficient in the fundamental principles and skills in Chinese civil law so as to be able to give informed advice on practical problems on Chinese civil law and to conduct advanced study and research in civil and commercial law of China;
• recognize and evaluate critically the differences in private law concepts and doctrines as well as practical operation thereof between Chinese civil law and Hong Kong common law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• acquire an advanced working knowledge of contract law of China;
• demonstrate a sophisticated understanding of the role and function of contract law in the Chinese society;
• be proficient in the fundamental doctrines and skills in Chinese contract law so as to be able to conduct advanced research and practice in Chinese contract law;
• be able to identify, analyze and critique on a comparative basis the development of Chinese contract law and the contract laws of other jurisdictions.

By the end of this course students will be able to:
• identify the key procedures of incorporating a business in mainland China;
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the structure and key characteristics of business organizations in China;
• describe the legal rights of shareholders and identify the legal remedies in the case of violations of those rights;
• comprehend the key legal aspects of corporate mergers and acquisitions;
• conduct independent legal research on topics relating to Chinese company law; and
• understand the application of Chinese company law in its distinctive political, economic, and social backgrounds.

Upon successful completion of this course students should be able to:
• understand the historical development and current significance of Mainland China’s foreign trade and investment laws;
• analyze critically the impact of China’s foreign trade and investment law on different levels;
• identify legal problems arising out of foreign trade and investment activities in Mainland China;
• conduct research in relation to the topics in Chinese foreign trade and investment law, and
• demonstrate and apply practical skills in the context of China’s trade and investment law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• acquire an advanced knowledge of law and practice of Chinese international law;
• demonstrate a sophisticated and critical understanding of the nature, role and functions of Chinese international law in its historical, social, economic and political context;
• gain the necessary skills to apply doctrines, principles and rules of Chinese international law to practical situations;
• formulate and communicate responses to issues of theoretical and/or practical significance in Chinese international law; and
• conduct advanced research on topics of Chinese international law and practice.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• acquire an advanced knowledge of law and practice of Chinese private international law;
• demonstrate a sophisticated and critical understanding of the nature, role and functions of Chinese private international law in its historical, social, economic and political context;
• gain the necessary skills to apply doctrines, principles and rules of Chinese private international law to practical situations;
• formulate and communicate responses to issues of theoretical and/or practical significance in Chinese private international law; and
• conduct advanced research on topics of Chinese private international law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• acquire an advanced knowledge of law and practice of Chinese civil procedure law;
• demonstrate a sophisticated and critical understanding of the nature, role and functions of Chinese civil procedure law in its historical, social, economic and political context and from a comparative perspective;
• gain the necessary skills to apply doctrines, principles and rules of Chinese civil procedure law to practical situations;
• formulate and communicate responses to issues of theoretical and/or practical significance in Chinese civil procedure law; and
• conduct advanced research on topics of Chinese civil procedure law.

Students who have successfully completed this course will be able to:
• demonstrate knowledge and understanding of the Chinese securities law relevant to the topics covered in the subject;
• make use of rules and regulations issued by the regulatory bodies when assessing the state of the law;
• identify and analyze the legal issues that typically arise in the subject area; and
• evaluate legal rules in the subject area from a comparative perspective.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• acquire an advanced knowledge of law and practice of Chinese intellectual property law;
• demonstrate a sophisticated and critical understanding of the nature, role and functions of Chinese intellectual property law in its historical, social, economic and political context and from a comparative perspective;
• gain the necessary skills to apply doctrines, principles and rules of Chinese intellectual property law to practical situations;
• formulate and communicate, both orally and in writing, responses to issues of theoretical and/or practical significance in Chinese intellectual property law; and
• conduct advanced research on topics of Chinese intellectual property law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• acquire an advanced knowledge of law and practice of Chinese banking law;
• demonstrate a sophisticated and critical understanding of the nature, role and functions of Chinese banking law in its historical, social, economic and political context and from a comparative perspective;
• gain the necessary skills to apply doctrines, principles and rules of Chinese banking law to practical situations;
• formulate and communicate responses to issues of theoretical and/or practical significance in Chinese banking law; and
• conduct advanced research on topics of Chinese banking law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• acquire a working knowledge of major Chinese environmental legal doctrines and regulatory mechanisms;
• demonstrate a broad understanding of the role and function of environmental law in the contemporary Chinese society;
• provide informed advice on Chinese environmental law to solve practical environmental problems;
• engage in critical and sophisticated analysis of Chinese environmental law and policy; and
• conduct advanced research on Chinese environmental law.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate awareness of the differences between various methods of dispute settlement in China, their Chinese characteristics, and their advantages and disadvantages;
• gain an understanding how the dispute resolution system is developed in China in its cultural and historical contexts;
• possess the knowledge and practical skills in international dispute settlement, including drafting an effective dispute resolution clause before disputes arise, choosing the effective means to settle the dispute when it arises, etc.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• gain an advanced understanding of the main constitutional and administrative principles, institutions and procedures in the PRC;
• discuss and analyze critically the views of leading practitioners, members of the judiciary and academics working in the areas of Chinese constitutional and administrative law;
• demonstrate an understanding of fundamental issues relating to rule of law, human rights, separation of powers and judicial review; and
• conduct advanced research on issues of Chinese constitutional and administrative law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• acquire an advanced knowledge of the dynamics between politics and law in contemporary China;
• demonstrate a sophisticated and critical understanding of the nature, role and key institutions of Chinese politics in its historical, social, and economic context and of how politics helps shape the legal system;
• gain the necessary skills to apply doctrines, principles and values of Chinese politics to practical law-related situations;
• formulate and communicate responses to issues of theoretical and/or practical significance in Chinese law and politics; and
• conduct advanced research on topics of Chinese law and politics.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• acquire an advanced knowledge of the law and finance in contemporary China;
• demonstrate a sophisticated and critical understanding of the nature, role and functions of Chinese finance in its historical, social, economic and legal context and of how the Chinese financial system interacts with the Chinese legal system;
• gain the necessary skills to apply doctrines, principles and rules of modern finance to practical law-related situations;
• formulate and communicate responses to issues of theoretical and/or practical significance in Chinese law and finance; and
• conduct advanced research on topics of Chinese law and finance.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• acquire an advanced knowledge of the law and accounting in contemporary China;
• demonstrate a sophisticated and critical understanding of the nature, role and functions of Chinese accounting in its historical, social, economic and legal context and of how the Chinese accounting system interacts with the Chinese legal system;
• gain the necessary skills to apply doctrines, principles and rules of modern accounting to practical law-related situations;
• formulate and communicate responses to issues of theoretical and/or practical significance in Chinese law and accounting; and
• conduct advanced research on topics of Chinese law and accounting.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• gain familiarity with the fundamental principles and concepts of Chinese property law;
• understand central practices in Chinese property law, for example, the mechanisms of the Chinese real estate market;
• gain an awareness of relevant social problems, for example those arising in the context of urban development; and
• acquire fluency in discussing the above issues.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• acquire an advanced knowledge of the law and economy in contemporary China;
• demonstrate a sophisticated and critical understanding of the nature, role and functions of Chinese economy in its historical, social, economic and legal context and of how the Chinese economic system interacts with the Chinese legal system;
• gain the necessary skills to apply doctrines, principles and rules of modern economy to practical law-related situations;
• formulate and communicate responses to issues of theoretical and/or practical significance in Chinese law and economy; and
• conduct advanced research on topics of Chinese law and economy.

Upon successful completion of this course students will be able to:
• appreciate the development of the PRC’s commercial law system in its historical, socio-economic and global context;
• conduct advanced research in relation to the topics covered by the course;
• have developed a critical understanding of key areas of the PRC’s commercial law; and
• demonstrate and apply practical legal skills in the area of Chinese commercial law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a well-founded understanding of the key institutions, fundamental principles, basic laws, rules and regulations regarding Chinese financial law;
• appreciate the historical, political and economic context in which Chinese financial law has evolved and operated, and the role of financial law in China’s economic and financial reforms;
• analyse the key issues and challenges relating to the regulation of financial institutions in China;
• apply the principles of Chinese financial law to practical situations;
• understand the implications of the CEPA to financial laws and regulations in China.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the practical context in which Chinese law and Chinese courts (or other legal institutions) operate;
• understand the working methods, principles and values in the practice of law in a Chinese court (or another legal institution);
• reflect critically on the legal practice in a Chinese court (or another legal institution) and its meaning and significance in society.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• acquire an advanced knowledge of law and practice of Chinese investment law;
• demonstrate a sophisticated and critical understanding of the nature, role and functions of Chinese investment law in its historical, social, economic and political context;
• gain the necessary skills to apply doctrines, principles and rules of Chinese investment law to practical situations; and
• formulate and communicate responses to issues of theoretical and/or practical significance in Chinese investment law.

By the end of this course and having done the required reading, discussion and writing, students will be able to:

• Articulate the various traits of the Chinese criminal justice regime and understand the social context within which criminal justice personnel and institutions operates;
• Gain a comprehensive understanding of research approaches and methodologies related to criminal justice matters;
• Being able to articulate a coherent and considered position on relevant issues.

After successfully completing this course, students should have understood:
• The systematic nature of the Common Law;
• How Common Law originates in judicial decisions;
• How English Common Law originated;
• The legal meaning of the term “case law”;
• The manner in which judges work when building the Common Law;
• The manner in which commonly held beliefs enter into the Common Law;
• The manner in which the Common Law remains stable while adapting to history; and
• The criteria a court applies when deciding whether to reject precedent.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• critically assess the contextual meaning of law, history and culture;
• appreciate the historical and cultural determination of law on the basis of traditional and modern scholarship;
• assess the interactive impact of history and culture on the development of law;
• evaluate the significance of history, culture and law especially in Hong Kong’s Chinese context.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• appreciate the value of comparative work in legal research and in legal practice;
• assess critically traditional and modern conceptual and methodological approaches in the area of comparative law;
• comprehend the actual and potential significance of comparative work in the areas of private law, public law (including criminal law) as well as at the public international law level;
• value the significance of different legal traditions and the phenomenon of mixed and harmonized jurisdictions including their historical developments in their respective societal, political and economic context;
• understand and apply comparative methodological tools in the areas of substantive and procedural law as well as in relation to legal skills.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the technology and the causes of action;
• describe the fundamental principles of copyright applied to this technology;
• describe international context of copyright and information technology.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand, analyze and define the main types of political regimes and State structures, to locate them in their context and to compare them;
• critically evaluate the advantages and drawbacks of different approaches to constitutional issues;
• determine the practical elements that should be implemented to ensure an efficient protection of human rights through the constitutional norm, constitutional courts and judicial review.

The aim is to ensure that by the end of the course students will:
• Possess substantive knowledge of the guiding principles and indicative detail of the Hong Kong law of unjust enrichment;
• Develop their skills of critical analysis and creative thought;
• Develop their skills of coherent argument and clear communication;
• Understand the place of unjust enrichment in the law of obligations and its practical use.

By the end of this course, students should be able to:
• Understand the problems in protecting different types of art, antiquities and cultural heritage;
• Understand the use of the common law to protect art, antiquities and cultural heritage;
• Critically analyze the protection of art, antiquities and cultural heritage in Hong Kong;
• Evaluate Hong Kong’s position in the international trade in art, antiquities and cultural heritage.

This Course aims to address the following skills. By the end of the course, students should be able to:
• Critically evaluate ongoing developments in law relating to cyber technologies.
• Display an understanding of how these developments relate to one another.
• Examine areas of doctrinal and political debate surrounding rules and theories in the field of cyber law;
• Evaluate those rules and theories in terms of internal coherence and practical outcomes;
• Draw on the analysis and evaluation contained in primary and secondary sources.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• assess and critique the merits and weaknesses of different scholarly arguments and
contentions;
• generate original theories, and produce compelling commentary articulating their arguments,
with reference to the sources;
• develop a critical, historically-informed approach towards contemporary legal structures.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

• Have knowledge of current legal principles and practices that relate to AI applications;

• Apply knowledge of current legal principles and practices to AI applications;

• Think analytically and philosophically about legal issues applied to AI;

• Assess AI’s impact on the future direction of law & the legal profession.

By the end of this course, students should be able to:
• distinguish the different forms of non-investment related international business transactions and governing legal concepts, structures and regimes;
• understand the impact of the law governing international trade and finance activities on different levels;
• identify legal problems arising out of cross-border trade scenarios and to assess the significance of various legal tools in order to address these problems;
• conduct research in relation to the topics discussed during the course;
• demonstrate and apply practical (e.g. negotiation, drafting, presentation, structured problem solving) skills in the context of international trade and finance.

By the end of this course, students should be able to:
• distinguish the different forms of investment related cross-border business transactions and governing legal concepts, structures and regimes;
• understand the impact of the law governing cross-border business transactions on different levels;
• identify legal problems arising out of cross-border investment scenarios and to assess the significance of various legal tools in order to address these problems;
• conduct research in relation to the topics discussed during the course;
• demonstrate and apply practical (e.g. negotiation, drafting, presentation, structured problem solving) skills required for legal work in the context of cross-border investment projects.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the basic normative and institutional components of international legal order with a special emphasis on the functions of international organizations and international dispute resolution mechanisms;
• understand the working of international law and institutions within the national legal orders and the response of the national legal orders to the demands of globalization of legal problems;
• appreciate and analyze critically the national and international legal framework for dealing with transnational problems that arise in Hong Kong, China and East Asia;
• have the necessary knowledge and skills.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:
• gain an understanding of the organisations, basic themes, laws, rules and regulations relating to international economic law;
• understand the role of government, the private sector and international organisations in economic development;
• receive information through a comparative perspective and thus be able to understand the variances of economic growth, protection and development in different countries;
• receive the necessary context to allow for engagement in international economic law practice in both public and private international law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the core principles of international trade law applicable to the regulation of international trade in goods, services, intellectual property and investment;
• understand the interpretation of the WTO and FTA legal texts;
• understand the WTO and FTA dispute settlement systems and decisions;
• understand the complex intersections between the regulation of international trade and domestic regulatory authorities;
• understand the intersection between law, economics, politics and public policy that inevitably occurs in any international trade negotiation or agreement.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• critically evaluate the contribution of legal institutions in the creation of strong and vibrant financial markets;
• identify the main components of the essential legal framework underpinning modern financial systems;
• identify and discuss the main components of the financial system, particularly the common law financial systems, European and Anglo-American;
• assess the importance of the quality of a country’s broader political and institutional framework for the development of an efficient, strong and honest financial market.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• explain the concepts covered in the course;
• apply them in an analytical fashion to a set of facts involving cross-border taxation of income (both business income and personal income).

By the end of the course, students will be able to:
• have a critical understanding of competition law;
• analyse current issues in competition law, both substantive and procedural;
• possess the capacity to explain the routes available to private parties in seeking remedies based on competition law;
• understand appeals procedures against public decisions on competition law;
• use research methods on competition law efficiently;
• deconstruct and solve a hypothetical legal problem related to competition law;
• competently construct written and oral legal arguments.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a sound and practical understanding of charterparty contracts and ocean bills of lading;
• refer to the sources of the Admiralty jurisdiction of the High Court of Hong Kong;
• identify the relevant law, procedures and practices to arrest and release a vessel in Hong Kong;
• consider the law and practices of insurance in the maritime context;
• demonstrate a sound and practical understanding of the laws and international conventions that govern limitation, collision, and salvage;
• identify key issues from the perspectives of cargo interests and of ship owners.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:
• gain an understanding of the basic themes, laws, rules and regulations governing intellectual property internationally;
• gain an appreciation – form an international perspective – of the central questions of substantive intellectual property law, especially copyright, trade mark and patent law, as well as understand some of the more important procedural issues relating to the protection of intellectual property internationally;
• receive the methodology necessary to allow for engagement in international intellectual property practice in both public and private international law;
• receive information through a comparative perspective and thus be able to understand the variances of protection in different countries.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• develop a sound understanding of the fundamental principles, processes and institutions of international environmental law;
• conduct advanced legal research on international environmental law;

• understand the context in which national environmental law develops and the way it relates to international principles;
• engage in critical analysis on the topic; and
• acquire the professional legal skills to advise clients and solve problems on issues relating to environmental law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the meaning of contracts in different legal traditions and their place in various societies in relation to other methods of economic and social co-ordination;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of the main legal rules and principles of contract across different legal traditions;
• demonstrate a deeper understanding of the common law of contract by comparing its rules, doctrines and underlying values to the contract law of other legal traditions;
• demonstrate an ability to apply the main contractual rules and principles of different legal traditions to formulate possible solutions to factual problems, and
• develop appropriate legal practice skills in relation to contractual rules and principles of different legal traditions.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• understand the nature of corporate governance and its place within company law;
• single out the main constituencies within a corporation and how their interests can conflict;
• assemble the arsenal of strategies and techniques various jurisdictions use to limit “agency costs”;
• understand how specific governance strategies and techniques work within specific, national corporate contexts; and
• design governance solutions to meet problems arising in different corporate contexts.

Successful completion of this course should enable you objectively to approach a foreign law and fully evaluate its regulatory impact on a stock corporation. You should receive a basic understanding of many aspects of company law in the United States, the United Kingdom and Germany, as well as how these sets of law may be distinguished from Hong Kong law. You will also see how on a global scale, ideas on and models of company law exercise their influence from one country to another.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• approach a foreign corporate law so as to accurately grasp its essential characteristics;
• look for rules of similar function and impact in different bodies of law;
• evaluate the real impact on a company of a jurisdiction’s company law rules;
• avoid home law bias when studying the foreign company law, and
• evaluate national company law according to the best global standards.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• have an awareness of the role and characteristics of the rules and legal principles relating to the business associations generally;
• have an awareness of the legitimate expectations of business parties and their legal obligations to each other and to third parties;
• have an awareness of the different types of business relationships and business contracts in Hong Kong
• understand the different objectives of business law in modern Hong Kong;
• understand the framework and different relationships in business law in Hong Kong; and
• understand the main issues, rules and legal principles relating to agency, partnership, employment, insurance and banking relationships;
• explain and demonstrate an understanding of the issues, rules and principles relating to business relationships and obligations to third parties;
• identify and critically evaluate Hong Kong business law;
• identify and critically evaluate the law relating to fiduciaries;
• explain and critically evaluate the law in relation to business entities and the legitimate expectations of business parties;
• understand legal analysis and the application of business law;
• put together legal arguments in a logical and persuasive manner.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical knowledge of the law relating to the internal market in the context of the EU;
• understand the institutional framework within which EU law is applied;
• apply their knowledge of EU law to hypothetical problems;
• write critically about the law and how it has developed in the context of the subject matter of the course;
• have developed an ability to research and apply both primary and secondary sources of EU law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the role of international law and politics in international society;
• demonstrate an appreciation of the relationship between methods of legal, political, economic and social co-ordination;
• demonstrate an ability to apply international relations theories and social science research skills in order to formulate possible solutions to current political problems;
• formulate oral arguments concerning international affairs and participate knowledgeably and effectively in debates.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a reasonable degree of knowledge of the nature of international organisations, including the origins and development of the International Monetary System, World Bank, and Basel.
• explain how the rules of international private law would apply to a particular accounting standard and what the outcome in such a situation would be;
• demonstrate, when discussing and writing about a particular accounting standard, an awareness of its characteristics, particularly those that distinguish it from others;
• when discussing any particular rule of international private law and a particular accounting standard, determine whether the rule in question derives from treaty or custom.

By taking this course, students will be able to:
• identify and analyse different theoretical models of international economics in light of ‘real world’ situations;
• assess the impact of the economies of regional integration and multilateral arrangements;
• critically evaluate the character and effect of globalisation, including the globalisation-growth-income poverty nexus;
• understand the economic underpinnings of many domestic and international rules.

By the end of this course, students will be able to
• appreciate the significance and complexity of legal skills in the multi-cultural and multi-jurisdictional context of international business transactions;
• have acquired advanced legal writing skills as required in cross-border transactional context;
• understand and be able to use specialized presentation and public speaking skills;
• know about the importance of financial documents in the context of cross-border business transactions, understand basic accounting principles and be able to read financial statements;
• conduct advanced research in relation to the topics addressed by the course.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• develop a good understanding of international investment law and the ability to apply it to hypothetical cases;
• appreciate the underlying policy issues at stake and how they interact with the existing legal framework;
• and be able to critically assess the rules, policies, and principles of international investment law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• think critically about the economic and political criteria that inform PTAs and reflect on the practice of PTAs in the context of the WTO;
• express the laws that regulate PTAs into applicable principles.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

• Develop skills in reading and critiquing contemporary legal scholarship in general, and in the field of tax law and policy in particular;
• Grasp key concepts of tax law and policy at a more nuanced and advanced level;
• Appreciate empirical and theoretical analysis of specific tax policy issues in a broader socioeconomic context; and
• Enhance techniques and understandings in interdisciplinary research.

By the end of the course, students should:

• possess a critical, thorough understanding of substantive and procedural aspects of merger control in Hong Kong, China the EU and the US;
• be familiar with the most controversial merger control cases, as well as ongoing investigations;
• be able to competently explain why merger transactions might be affected by various legal regimes, and to advise companies on how best to deal with merger investigations in Hong Kong and elsewhere;
• improve oral and written communications skills by competently constructing legal arguments.

By the end of the course, students should:

• have a critical understanding of specific problems relating to this field of the law;
• understand how the classic competition law discussions apply in the Hong Kong and Mainland China context;
• identify specific problems relating to the application of competition law in Hong Kong and Mainland China;
• be able to analyse and critically discuss current issues in competition law in Hong Kong and Mainland China;
• understand the extent to which the solutions applied elsewhere to these problems a) have been successful and b) are useful in the Hong Kong context;
• improve their oral presentational and debate skills through individual presentations and debates;
• use research methods on competition law efficiently;
• competently construct written and oral (substantiated) legal arguments.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

* possess a critical, thorough understanding of the regulatory challenges associated with the Digital Age in general and the platform economy in particular;
* competently advise companies, platform users and workers on how best to comply with the law and exercise their legal rights;
* reflect critically on how the current legal framework can address the new ‘digitalized’ reality, and propose normative solutions where necessary;
* recognize and rationalize the most important cases and investigations relating to the digital economy, and apply that knowledge to new practical scenarios;
* grasp the need to balance the innovative potential of the digital economy with the risks associated with the power amassed by platform ecosystems and their social responsibility;
* improve oral and written communications skills by competently constructing legal arguments, and conducting legal research.

By the end of this course, you will be able to:
• Diagram and explain the structure of a typical project finance transaction;
• Identify the key actors in a project financing and their roles;
• Understand the fundamental risks in a project financing and the basic ways to mitigate them;
• Explain the main provisions of key project contracts and redraft them based on client instructions;
• Explain the main provisions of key finance documents and redraft them based on client instructions; and
• Understand how projects go bad and some of the key mechanisms to get them back on track.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

* Understand the specific nature of clean technology law and critically reflect on the main principles of law in this field;
* Understand the main regulatory approaches used by states to promote the financial viability of new technologies in the energy sector and facilitate their deployment;
* Understand the main principles of international economic law applicable to the clean technology transition;
* Identify the main challenges regarding the reorganization of existing energy systems towards sustainability and decarbonization.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

• Understand the specific nature of oil and gas regulation and critically reflect on the main principles of law in this field;
• Identify the main ownership and licensing regimes that can apply to the oil and gas sector, and critically reflect on the advantages and disadvantages of different regulatory approaches in this field;
• Understand the main contractual approaches that are used in the oil and gas industry, and critically reflect on the advantages and disadvantages of these approaches from an investor and state’s perspective;
• Understand the main regulatory techniques applied to limit the risk of environmental pollution in the energy sector.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

• Identify and critically reflect on the commercial, investment and trade-related risks that can affect energy investments (electricity projects, oil and gas, renewable energy);
• Understand the different dispute resolution options available to energy investors;
• Interpret and apply dispute resolution (arbitration) clauses in investment agreements and investment treaties;
• Identify and critically reflect on the main mechanisms of investor protection in energy agreements;
• Interpret the substantive investment protection disciplines of investment treaties and apply these disciplines to investment disputes in the energy sector (termination of investment agreement, change to tax regime, termination of renewable energy subsidies, energy tariff issues);
• Understand and critically reflect on the limits of investment protection in the field of environmental and energy security regulation;
• Understand the application of world trade law to the energy sector, with a focus on subsidies, local content requirements, and energy transit;

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

• Identify and understand the Hong Kong and international sources of the law on disaster risk reduction and responsiveness;

• Explain different legal models for disaster risk regulation and reduction;

• Understand and explain the contribution of the precautionary principle to disaster risk reduction;

• Understand the contribution which international environmental law can make to disaster risk prevention and reduction;

• Understand and explain different legal approaches to responding to and remediating natural and man made disasters, such as governmental and private insurance arrangements, compensation and the ‘polluter pays’ principle;

• Explain the impact of energy undertakings on the natural environment and the contribution which their operations can make to disaster risks;

• Understand and explain the role of various regulatory models on energy undertakings, with a view to ensuring compliance with disaster prevention and reduction responsibilities;

• Explain and understand the various international bodies and agencies involved in the disparate fields of preventing, managing and responding to the manifold sources of disaster risks;

• Understand the unequal distribution of disaster risk at a global level, including as a result of climate change, and the implications of this for the global commons, migration and human rights.

The aim of the course is to provide students with a greater understanding of the nature of law and of the manner in which law has evolved through a broad overview of the global history of law. By the end of this course, students will:

• Understand better the variety of roles law can play and has played in society;

• Be familiar with an extensive range of historical and theoretical scholarship relating to legal history;

• Be able to assess and critique the merits and weaknesses of different scholarly arguments and contentions;

• Develop a critical, historically-informed approach to contemporary legal structures;

• Develop original reflections on law’s history and functions in society.

By the end of this course, students will:

• Have developed their research and writing skills;

• Have greater insight into the mechanics and practice of developing research questions and methodologies designed to answer such questions, including legal history methodology in particular;

• Have greater insight into historiography and the theory of legal history;

• Have an enhanced ability to give presentations of their work, and to give and receive constructive criticism;

• Have a wider awareness of different sorts of projects one may pursue within the general area of legal history.

By the end of this course, students will:

• Have developed their research and writing skills;

• Have greater insight into the mechanics and practice of developing research questions and methodologies designed to answer such questions, including legal history methodology in particular;

• Have greater insight into historiography and the theory of legal history;

• Have an enhanced ability to give presentations of their work, and to give and receive constructive criticism;

• Have a wider awareness of different sorts of projects one may pursue within the general area of legal history.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate an ability to conduct legal research;
• write a substantial legal paper.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate an ability to conduct high level legal research;
• write a very substantial legal paper.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

• demonstrate a critical understanding of the role and characteristics of a partnership in Hong Kong law;

• demonstrate a critical understanding of the role and characteristics of a private limited liability company;

• describe the structure and formal arrangements of a Hong Kong private limited liability company with a particular emphasis on majority rule and the constitutional documents;

• describe the different sources of Hong Kong law for the incorporation and management of a company and the division of powers between the Board of Directors and the shareholders in general meeting;

• explain the different ways that the company's constitution can be altered and the significance of the Memorandum and Articles of Association;

• demonstrate an understanding of the meaning of "shares" in company law and the different ways that shares can be allocated and transferred;

• explain the law relating to the appointment ,tenure and removal of directors and directors' duties;

• demonstrate an understanding of the meaning of corporate personality, corporate authority and agency problems in company law;

• explore shareholder rights and remedies and the legal issues relevant to company meetings and shareholder resolutions;

• demonstrate a critical understanding of the role and characteristics of share capital and class rights in a private limited liability company;

• describe the meaning and characteristics of debt and equity capital in a private limited liability company;

• demonstrate an understanding of the law relating to groups of companies;

• explain the law relating to section 168A petitions and the law on statutory derivative actions and minority shareholders' rights generally;

• demonstrate an understanding of the law relating to fixed and floating charges;

• demonstrate an understanding of the law relating to Romalpa clauses, the doctrine of relation back and fraudulent preference as they relate to the supply of credit to a company;

• demonstrate an understanding of insolvency law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

• understand the role of the judge and the jury in relation to the admissibility/assessment of evidence;
• ascertain who bears the burden of proof in respect of any given case or issue in a case, and explain to what standard facts must be proved in various civil and criminal contexts;
• understand how rules governing the admissibility of evidence work in practice;
• place the rules of evidence within their wider historical, social and psychological context;
• solve problem questions which require research into, understanding and application of the main rules of evidence governing proof of facts in criminal and civil trials.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the meaning of “constitutional law” and the differences between constitutional and administrative law;
• describe the fundamental principles of constitutional law;
• demonstrate an understanding of the differences and interrelationship of constitutional and administrative in the context of the political and administrative system in Hong Kong;
• describe the Basic Law and its relationship to international law and the constitutional system of the People’s republic of China;
• demonstrate an understanding of selected rights and freedoms of residents of Hong Kong in the context of the Basic Law;
• identify constitutional issues and the role of law and government;
• describe the relationship of the Basic Law and the Hong Kong court system;
• conduct basic legal research and make formal presentations to the class.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of commercial law;
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the law relating to consumer protection in Hong Kong law, including The Sale of Goods Ordinance, the Moneylenders Ordinance and the Control of Exemption Clauses Ordinance;
• describe specific commercial transactions from the perspective of the supplier and creditor;
• demonstrate an understanding of the different types of choses in action and how they may be assigned;
• explain significant aspects of security interests and how they are used in commercial law in Hong Kong;
• explain the relevance of bills of exchange, negotiable instruments and aspects of banking law in commercial law;
• explain the relevant law relating to personal property, interests in personal property and rights of possession;
• explain the relevance of the law relating to the nemo dat rule, exceptions to the rule and the law on gifts and conditional gifts in the commercial law context;
• demonstrate an understanding of bankruptcy law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• outline the history of the development of equity;
• describe the role, function, strengths and limitations of equity;
• explain the history, development, role and function of the trust;
• summarise and explain key provisions of the law governing trusts in Hong Kong;
• provide basic legal advice in the area of equity and trusts;
• describe the remedies developed by equity;
• give an educated opinion of the future of equity;
• evaluate the trust as it functions in Hong Kong;
• appreciate the role that trust play in modern society.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the development of land law and its economic and social importance;
• develop awareness of the development of land law in other common law jurisdictions;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of the principles and legal rules of land law;
• understand in outline how the principles and legal rules apply to transactions involving land;
• identify facts and issues and apply the principles and rules to resolve legal problems;
• conduct legal research and formulate arguments; and
• write clearly, logically and accurately.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the administrative law’s place in society in relation to other methods of economic and social co-ordination;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of the main legal rules and principles of administrative law;
• identify legal problems involving those rules and principles;
• demonstrate an ability to apply the main rules and principles of administrative law to formulate possible solutions to factual problems;
• conduct basic legal research, and formulate oral arguments concerning the rules and principles of administrative law.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:

• demonstrate a critical understanding of the meaning of contracts and their place in society in relation to other methods of economic and social co-ordination;

• demonstrate a sound knowledge of the main legal rules and principles of contract;

• identify legal problems involving those rules and principles;

• demonstrate an ability to apply the main rules and principles of contract to formulate possible solutions to factual problems, and

• conduct basic legal research and formulate oral arguments concerning the rules and principles of contract.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the meaning of crime and its place in society in relation to other methods of regulation and social control;
• describe the fundamental principles of criminal liability;
• describe selected criminal offences, their structure, basis and operational basis;
• identify and solve criminal problems, and
• conduct basic legal research and make formal presentations to the class.

By the end of this course, students will be able to:
• demonstrate a critical understanding of the meaning of torts and their place in society in relation to other methods of economic and social co-ordination;
• demonstrate a sound knowledge of the main legal rules and principles of tort;
• identify legal problems involving those rules and principles;
• demonstrate an ability to apply the main rules and principles of tort to formulate possible solutions to factual problems, and
• conduct basic legal research and formulate oral arguments concerning the rules and principles of tort.

After taking this course, students should have the capacity to:
- in formulating a thesis, approach a field of academic literature and discern areas, questions and arguments that have not yet been fully or accurately addressed;
- build a complex argument that distinguishes itself through originality, either supplementing or improving upon existing scholarship;
- break an in-depth argument regarding a complex thesis topic down into discrete chapter units and express the argument in writing, using ample support and a coherent and convincing structure;
- conduct research and draft scholarship based on that research without close and regular supervision; and
- present ideas orally and in writing to an audience of one's peers.
